past with Jon Meacham, author of
"Destiny

10:26.759 --> 10:30.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Power: The American Odyssey
of George
Herbert Walker Bush."

10:30.563 --> 10:35.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Nancy Gibbs, she's editor in
chief at
"TIME" magazine and the
co-author of "The

10:35.969 --> 10:36.936 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Presidents Club."

10:36.970 --> 10:39.005 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you back
to the program.

10:39.038 --> 10:40.740 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jon Meacham, to you first.

10:40.773 --> 10:44.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know we don't have a lot to go
on, just
that short photo opportunity in
the Oval Office,

10:44.711 --> 10:47.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but how did it look to you that
this transition
is getting off?

10:48.014 --> 10:51.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JON MEACHAM, Presidential
Historian: Well,
better than expected, given that
48 hours

10:51.251 --> 10:53.653 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ago they were at each other's
throats.

10:53.686 --> 10:58.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So the bar has been lowered in
many ways in
this campaign.

10:58.525 --> 11:01.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so why wouldn't that be true
in terms
of a transition?

11:01.961 --> 11:05.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that President Obama has
hit all the
right notes.

11:05.198 --> 11:09.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that president-elect
Trump has hit
all the right notes since
election night,

11:09.168 --> 11:10.937 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as did Secretary Clinton.

11:10.970 --> 11:15.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think that this may be
the shortest
honeymoon ever, but at least
it's a period

11:15.675 --> 11:17.744 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of some tranquility after the
storm.

11:17.777 --> 11:23.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Nancy Gibbs, as
someone who
has studied transitions going
back for many

11:23.049 --> 11:24.851 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
presidents, how does this one
look so far?

11:24.884 --> 11:29.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NANCY GIBBS, "TIME": Well, it
looks actually
like a pattern we have seen
before, which

11:29.355 --> 11:35.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is two politicians of different
parties who
have been very tough as
political opponents

11:35.962 --> 11:39.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who very quickly come together
when they find
themselves in a new position.

11:39.766 --> 11:46.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This tradition goes back to
1952, when Harry
Truman invited the newly elected
Dwight Eisenhower

11:46.506 --> 11:49.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to the White House after
Eisenhower's election.

11:49.576 --> 11:53.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those two men could not stand
each other and
were barely on speaking terms.

11:53.546 --> 11:55.381 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They were very, very bitter
rivals.

11:55.415 --> 12:01.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And yet Truman, who himself had
taken office
with no preparation so suddenly
when Franklin

12:01.220 --> 12:05.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Roosevelt died, felt, in the
nuclear age it
was just too dangerous for
anyone to walk

12:05.758 --> 12:07.627 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
into the Oval Office unprepared.

12:07.660 --> 12:14.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so he invited Eisenhower to
come, briefed
him, had the Cabinet secretaries
meet.

12:14.267 --> 12:18.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Eisenhower in turn did the same
thing with
John F. Kennedy, once again a
young man from

12:18.438 --> 12:22.442 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
a different party whom
Eisenhower had very
little respect for.

12:22.475 --> 12:23.743 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But they respect the office.

12:23.776 --> 12:26.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they particularly respect
the demands
of it.

12:26.479 --> 12:30.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they want to make sure that
the guy who
is coming in to take over
understands just

12:30.183 --> 12:31.951 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what it is that he's facing.

12:31.985 --> 12:35.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, a lot of us
don't realize
that it's been -- there's been
bitterness

12:35.221 --> 12:37.190 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going back for a long time.

12:37.223 --> 12:43.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jon Meacham, what are examples
of what -- of
a transition that has worked
well, where it

12:43.796 --> 12:48.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has -- where the two sides have
had to overcome
some challenges, but they have
made it happen?

12:48.968 --> 12:51.070 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON MEACHAM: Well, I don't think
we have to
go back very far.

12:51.104 --> 12:57.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, if you go back to the
dismal autumn
of 2008, when a lot of people
believed that

12:57.343 --> 13:03.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the economy, I think, as
President Bush put
it at the time, that the sucker
could go down,

13:03.049 --> 13:07.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and there were an enormous
number of emergency
financial steps that had to be
taken.

13:07.553 --> 13:12.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have heard both President
Obama and
President Bush talk about how
smooth that

13:12.125 --> 13:13.526 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
transition was.

13:13.559 --> 13:18.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think, as Nancy says, it
speaks well
of the office.

13:18.164 --> 13:24.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other factor here, I think,
is politicians
admire vote-getters, even if
they disagree

13:24.370 --> 13:27.473 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with everything that they did to
get the votes.

13:27.507 --> 13:34.247 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so there's a certain
clubbiness here,
that they respect strength, they
respect those

13:34.280 --> 13:36.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who master the world that they
have mastered.

13:36.549 --> 13:41.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I suspect -- though
President Obama might
not admit it, I suspect that
somewhere in

13:41.688 --> 13:48.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his being, there's a curiosity
about this
man who has shaken up American
politics so

13:48.461 --> 13:49.429 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
profoundly.

13:49.462 --> 13:51.230 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What about that,
Nancy Gibbs?

13:51.264 --> 13:56.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What are some of the factors
that might lend
themselves to a more successful
handover of

13:56.369 --> 13:58.237 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
power?

13:58.271 --> 14:02.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NANCY GIBBS: One thing I think
that is important
to bear in mind is, some part of
this is very

14:02.175 --> 14:07.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
practical about the nuts and
bolts of a smooth
transition, not just at the
level of president

14:07.513 --> 14:12.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to president, but Cabinet
members, White House
staff members, national security
officials,

14:12.852 --> 14:16.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of having as much communication
as possible,
so that that goes smoothly.

14:16.923 --> 14:18.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But some part of this is
theater.

14:18.791 --> 14:23.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think particularly after a
very bitter
campaign of the kind that we
just saw, there's

14:23.596 --> 14:28.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a recognition that the country
needs to see
this, that the world needs to
see it, that

14:28.601 --> 14:33.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the country comes first and the
well-being
of the people comes first, and
to see these

14:33.773 --> 14:39.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
two teams working together is an
important
part of sort of national
reconciliation.

14:40.012 --> 14:45.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Jon Meacham,
how much
has that played into transition
in the past,

14:45.618 --> 14:51.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because -- especially right now,
these two
men have their own differences,
but we're

14:51.290 --> 14:53.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
watching a country that's still
very divided.

14:53.259 --> 14:55.661 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JON MEACHAM: Oh, absolutely.

14:55.695 --> 15:01.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The first peaceful transfer from
one party
in power to the other party was
in 1800.

15:01.801 --> 15:06.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was a very close-run
thing because
of a controversy with the
election between

15:06.305 --> 15:13.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Adams and Jefferson, and they
were insistent
that the constitutional order
clean up that

15:13.579 --> 15:17.016 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
anomaly in the Electoral College
and make
this transition happen.

15:17.049 --> 15:18.851 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That set a pattern.

15:18.885 --> 15:23.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the remarkable things,
when you think
about it, is that we had in the
Union states

15:23.923 --> 15:26.726 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
an election in 1864.

15:26.759 --> 15:32.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are certain -- to go to
Nancy's point,
there are certain rituals that
send an important

15:32.365 --> 15:37.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cultural and political signal
that the body
politic is intact.

15:37.103 --> 15:40.039 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It may be fighting each other.

15:40.072 --> 15:46.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One arm may be trying to punch
the other fist,
but, ultimately, it is one
country, and the

15:46.412 --> 15:48.748 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
political order is bigger than
any one person.

15:48.781 --> 15:52.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Nancy Gibbs,
if you're
Donald Trump, the
president-elect, what are

15:52.285 --> 15:57.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
