very, very resilient,
and I think was in -- ISIS was
in for a surprise.

48:21.599 --> 48:25.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER LIVESAY: But the
attack may have
aggravated ethnic tensions.

48:25.035 --> 48:30.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Amnesty International and the
United Nations
have accused Kurdish authorities
of driving

48:30.508 --> 48:34.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hundreds of Arab families out of
the city
in an act of retaliation.

48:34.945 --> 48:37.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NAJMALDIN KARIM: First of all,
that's not
true.

48:37.982 --> 48:44.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Several hundred families is
nothing compared
to 115 (INAUDIBLE) and families
who are all

48:44.955 --> 48:46.490 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Sunni Arabs in this city.

48:46.524 --> 48:50.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If there was such a policy, none
of these
would have been allowed to come
in.

48:50.261 --> 48:55.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER LIVESAY: Kirkuk is a
melting pot
of virtually every ethnic group
in Iraq, Kurds,

48:55.366 --> 48:57.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Turkmen, and Arabs.

48:57.101 --> 49:03.240 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They have co-existed for
centuries, but tensions
are not uncommon, and sometimes
violent.

49:03.274 --> 49:08.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ISIS, which is made up of
Sunnis, has exploited
those tensions, and depended on
the support

49:08.345 --> 49:11.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of sympathetic Sunni Arabs
across Iraq and
Syria.

49:11.649 --> 49:15.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, in Kirkuk, that alliance
appears weak.

49:15.152 --> 49:20.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During our interview with the
governor, a
Sunni Arab named Mohammed Jawad
Ali Jasim

49:20.624 --> 49:22.092 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
arrived to tell us his story.

49:22.126 --> 49:24.562 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NAJMALDIN KARIM: He says he
killed two ISIS.

49:24.595 --> 49:29.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER LIVESAY: He says
ISIS militants
stormed into his home seeking
refuge.

49:29.567 --> 49:35.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Instead, Jasim says he shot two
of them dead
with his own AK-47.

49:35.139 --> 49:40.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Out of desperation, the third
attacker detonated
a suicide bomb, wounding him.

49:40.277 --> 49:46.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sheik Anwar Al-Asi is the emir
of the Al-Ubaid
Tribes, a prominent Sunni in
both Kirkuk,

49:46.750 --> 49:48.986 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as well as ISIS-held territory.

49:49.019 --> 49:53.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says that many Sunnis,
including members
of his tribes, supported ISIS at
the beginning.

49:53.991 --> 49:57.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHEIKH ANWAR AL-ASI, Emir,
Al-Ubaid Tribes
(through translator): There is
some.

49:57.394 --> 49:59.129 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I can't deny that.

49:59.163 --> 50:00.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There is a section that helps
ISIS.

50:00.965 --> 50:04.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER LIVESAY: Those views
have made
him a target.

50:04.301 --> 50:10.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two years ago, ISIS blew up his
home near
Kirkuk when he refused to join
their alliance.

50:10.641 --> 50:13.477 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course, its riches aren't
limited to cultural
diversity.

50:13.510 --> 50:16.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Kirkuk is a trove of natural
resources.

50:16.513 --> 50:21.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This oil field and others like
it make Kirkuk
the largest producer oil
producer in all of

50:21.151 --> 50:23.120 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Northern Iraq.

50:23.153 --> 50:28.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that makes Kirkuk an even
more attractive
prize to Islamic State, which
fueled its unprecedented

50:28.359 --> 50:33.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
expansion across Iraq and Syria
in large part
by selling crude on the black
market.

50:34.031 --> 50:39.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These fields are just a short
distance from
Hawija, a vast area held by ISIS
on the border

50:39.069 --> 50:41.572 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Kirkuk.

50:41.605 --> 50:46.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Amir Taleb Faruq commands the
Hawija front
line for the Peshmerga, the
Kurdish military

50:46.410 --> 50:50.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
force that's been the most
successful bulwark
against ISIS since its invasion.

50:51.015 --> 50:55.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMIR TALEB FARUQ, Peshmerga
Commander (through
translator): ISIS attacked over
in this area

50:55.953 --> 50:57.454 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
six days ago.

50:57.488 --> 51:00.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, just as in the past, we
subdued them,
and they didn't break through.

51:00.824 --> 51:04.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER LIVESAY: Moments
later, an explosion
in ISIS territory.

51:05.029 --> 51:07.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Smoke billows from a white
building.

51:07.364 --> 51:12.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Coalition forces launched an
airstrike on
the same area the night before.

51:12.069 --> 51:18.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Coalition airstrikes have been
instrumental
in repelling ISIS from Kirkuk.

51:18.042 --> 51:23.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Major General Westa Rasul shows
us some armored
ISIS vehicles they captured
after a battle.

51:23.781 --> 51:25.349 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're known as death cars.

51:25.382 --> 51:26.350 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
MAJ.

51:26.383 --> 51:28.252 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

51:28.285 --> 51:31.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WESTA RASUL, Peshmerga (through
translator):
Last year, ISIS sent three of
these cars towards

51:31.155 --> 51:32.222 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Kirkuk.

51:32.256 --> 51:33.958 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Two of them were halted.

51:33.991 --> 51:38.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of them made it three
kilometers past
the Peshmerga front line,
because nothing

51:38.095 --> 51:39.596 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can stop these things.

51:39.630 --> 51:42.499 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER LIVESAY: These ISIS
death traps
are virtually indestructible.

51:42.533 --> 51:44.001 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RPGs can't take them out.

51:44.034 --> 51:46.203 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Machine gun fire can't take them
out.

51:46.236 --> 51:47.271 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But airstrikes can.

51:47.304 --> 51:49.073 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And one did in this case.

51:49.106 --> 51:53.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is the exit wound of an
airplane that
fired down a missile on this
thing and took

51:53.043 --> 51:54.578 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it out.

51:54.611 --> 51:58.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Peshmerga and the Iraqi army
now have
Hawija surrounded, says the
general.

51:58.482 --> 52:03.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the border is vast and, in
some places,
porous, despite a sprawling wall
the Peshmerga

52:03.654 --> 52:06.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have built between Kirkuk and
the Islamic
State.

52:06.890 --> 52:11.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's believed that the fighters
who launched
the attack on Kirkuk came from
this area,

52:11.795 --> 52:13.230 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and locals fear they could come
again.

52:13.263 --> 52:14.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MUSTAFA MOHAMMED: You get used
to it.

52:14.565 --> 52:15.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER LIVESAY: So, it
might happen again.

52:15.866 --> 52:16.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's just that you're not
worried.

52:16.867 --> 52:17.835 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MUSTAFA MOHAMMED: It might be.

52:17.868 --> 52:18.836 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It might be.

52:18.869 --> 52:20.404 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I don't know.

52:20.437 --> 52:22.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER LIVESAY: But that
isn't stopping
him from rebuilding his hotels.

52:22.840 --> 52:27.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Despite the risks from ISIS and
lingering
sectarian divisions in Kirkuk,
he says the

52:27.578 --> 52:29.113 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
city will endure.

52:29.146 --> 52:31.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Kirkuk will outlive ISIS, he
says.

52:31.815 --> 52:34.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the future of Iraq is less
certain.

52:34.718 --> 52:40.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Christopher Livesay
in Kirkuk.

